BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:BUAOc5lwmsyto5u5vSgpZ
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260301T153235Z
DTSTART:20260305T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-05T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-05T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hpymx0WEZ3n6HlmlCAycp
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260301T153235Z
DTSTART:20260305T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	3-05T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-03-05T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:Zjou8XYxbjA9EScGfTpdg
SUMMARY:Free First
DTSTAMP:20260301T153235Z
DTSTART:20260305T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Call your friends and bring the family\, admission is FREE to e
	veryone at the Seattle Art Museum on the first Thursday of every month. In
	 addition to our regular hours\, Seattle Art Museum will be open for Free 
	First Thursday evenings from 5-8 pm to provide more opportunities to visit
	 the galleries for free! Evening hours will feature extra activities like 
	live music\, drop-in art making\, and in-gallery experiences for visitors.
	 Tickets are available both onsite and online. 10-8 pm | Beyond Mysticism:
	 The Modern Northwest opening day 4th floor galleries 11:30 am\, 1:30 pm |
	 Public Tour: Highlights from SAM's Collection These 60-minute tours meet 
	at the top of the 3rd floor escalators. 5-8 pm | Design your own tarot car
	d with Imani Sims Take inspiration from SAM's permanent collection to crea
	te your own tarot card. What symbols represent you? Brotman Forum 5:30-6:3
	0 pm | SAM Gallery artist talk SAM Gallery 6 pm | Beyond Mysticism Public 
	Tour This 60-minute tour meets at the 4th floor special exhibition entranc
	e Free First Thursday Evenings Presented by\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.co
	m/events/#/details/free-first/17799809/2026-03-05T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Ar
	ts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/free-first/17799809/2026-
	03-05T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT10H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:QHAhtAj7wbjfUJXyRIeyS
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260301T153235Z
DTSTART:20260305T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nhttps://seatoday.
	6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geometry-of-light/16795597
	/2026-03-05T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-03-05T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:_MLHaJpaijqg0gS4xGTRh
SUMMARY:Antique Fire Truck Exhibition -- Discover Seattle's firefighting he
	ritage!
DTSTAMP:20260301T153235Z
DTSTART:20260305T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:Event Overview  At the Last Resort Fire Department Museum\, vis
	itors step into Seattle's rich firefighting past through an impressive col
	lection of antique fire apparatus and historic artifacts dating from 1913 
	to 1969. Housed inside the Seattle Fire Department Headquarters in Pioneer
	 Square\, the museum showcases meticulously restored engines\, ladder truc
	ks\, equipment\, photographs\, and memorabilia that highlight the evolutio
	n of the Seattle Fire Department and the dedicated volunteers who preserve
	d its legacy. Guests can expect an up-close look at iconic rigs\, includin
	g the city's only Ahrens-Fox\, as well as stories and displays that bring 
	to life more than 50 years of community service\, fire prevention history\
	, and vintage firehouse craftsmanship.  Open and free to all every Thursda
	y. Check Last Resort Fire Department website for details.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/antique-fire-truck-exhibition-discover-se
	attle-s-firefighting-heritage/17827865/2026-03-05T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Ar
